    {
      "text": "A 28-year-old woman with a known history of beta-thalassemia undergoes a blood transfusion. During the transfusion, she develops symptoms of anxiety, hypotension, and fever. What is the next appropriate step in the management of this patient?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Stop the blood transfusion and restart after stabilization"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Continue the blood transfusion and perform an ECG"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Investigate for clerical errors in the blood transfusion process"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Administer corticosteroids and monitor vital signs"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: A) Stop the blood <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> and restart after stabilization</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p>In a woman with beta-thalassemia experiencing anxiety, hypotension, and fever during transfusion, the immediate step is to stop the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> and ensure stabilization.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Transfusion Reactions:</strong></p>\n\n<p>It refers to an adverse response to blood components, which can be</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Immunologically mediated (via WBC)</li>\n\t<li>Related to infections.</li>\n\t<li>It can either be immediate or delayed.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:bottom\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Aspect</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:bottom\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Immediate <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">Transfusion</span> Reactions</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:bottom\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Delayed <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">Transfusion</span> Reactions</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Onset Time</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Within hours of transfusion</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Days to weeks after transfusion</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Cause</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Immunologic reactions, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d30ae941d516927771889351160b00\">hemolytic</span> or non-hemolytic</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Immune-mediated, often involving minor <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"782b31281a1692777181708484c1d1\">antigen</span> sensitization</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Presentation </strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Fever, chills, Dyspnea (TRALI, TACO), <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">Acute</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cfad80a0f716927771979aae100f95\">respiratory</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"afafb9026e1692777186e3dd168fa8\">distress</span> (TRALI), Pulmonary oedema (TACO), hypothermia, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"2e0552462e16927771871413861fb7\">electrolyte</span> abnormalities, coagulopathy, acid-base disorders and hyperkalemia</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Fever, jaundice, Gradual decline in haemoglobin levels (hemolysis)</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Severity</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Can range from mild to life-threatening</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Generally less severe than immediate reactions</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Examples</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Febrile non-hemolytic reaction (FNHTR)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Transfusion-related <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> lung injury (TRALI)</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Transfusion-associated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f3739d892c1692777184b2e134615c\">circulatory</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9d02a99d051692777194aa3375023b\">overload</span> (TACO)</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-left:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-right:1px solid #0d0d0d; border-top:1px solid #0d0d0d; vertical-align:middle\">\n\t\t\t<p>Delayed <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d30ae941d516927771889351160b00\">hemolytic</span> reaction</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Management </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Stop the blood transfusion.</li>\n\t<li>Supportive care.</li>\n\t<li>Three samples are to be collected\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Blood\n\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t<li>1st sample: For BG/CM (blood <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d5b9840ce01692777188803b4c75b4\">grouping</span> - cross matching) (EDTA vial)</li>\n\t\t\t<li>2nd sample: Biochemical test for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c2b082746716927771888f0933941d\">hemolysis</span> (plain red vial)</li>\n\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</li>\n\t\t<li>Urine\n\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t<li>Test for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ddeb334a351692777188795bb090ef\">hemoglobinuria</span> (hemolysis).</li>\n\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Continue the blood <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> and perform an ECG </strong><strong>(Option B)</strong>: Continuing the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> could worsen the reaction. The first step in managing a suspected <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> reaction is stopping the transfusion.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Investigate for clerical errors in the blood <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> process</strong><strong> (Option C)</strong>: While clerical errors (e.g., <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8cb71c753c16927771831c74cb7271\">blood type</span> mismatch) are important to rule out, the immediate priority is to stop the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> and stabilize the patient before investigating further.</p>\n\n<p><br />\n<strong>Administer corticosteroids and monitor vital signs</strong><strong> (Option D)</strong>: Corticosteroids may be used in certain reactions (such as allergic reactions), but the <strong>first step</strong> should be stopping the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> and addressing any immediate complications (e.g., hypotension, fever). Corticosteroids are not the first-line treatment for most <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cbb73554631692777200444a9ea263\">transfusion</span> reactions.</p>",
