      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: C) The fall in 2,3-DPG is less</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>2,3-DPG (2,3-diphosphoglycerate)</strong> is important for facilitating oxygen release from haemoglobin to tissues. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ff21381a7a1692777185cb873396da\">CPD</span> helps maintain higher levels of 2,3-DPG during blood storage compared to ACD, which is crucial for better oxygen delivery to tissues.</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>2,3-DPG is a molecule that binds to haemoglobin, promoting the release of oxygen to tissues.</li>\n\t<li>During blood storage, 2,3-DPG levels gradually decrease.</li>\n\t<li>A reduction in 2,3-DPG leads to a leftward shift in the oxygen <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"18fb34ab321692777186e9bc95a726\">dissociation</span> curve, which decreases oxygen release to tissues.</li>\n\t<li>This can be harmful to hypoxic patients, as they already have compromised oxygen delivery</li>\n</ul>",
